soft-rayed and spiny-rayed fish)	DACTYLOPTERIFORMES (greatly enlarged pectoral fins that resemble wings)	DIPTERIFORMES (= Dipnoi, lungfish, can breathe air)	ELOPIFORMES (single dorsal fin with only soft rays)	GADIFORMES (cods & hakes)	GASTEROSTEIFORMES (ray-finned fish that includes sea horses, pipefishes, and sticklebacks)	GONORHYNCHIFORMES (ray-finned fish with small mouths and no fish)	MEGALOPIFORMES	MYCTOPHIFORMES (small fish with subterminal mouths with numerous tiny teeth and light-producing organs)	OPHIDIIFORMES (ray-finned fish that resemble eels, have long dorsal fins and an anal fin)	OSMERIFORMES (generally silvery and elongate fish)	OSTEOGLOSSIFORMES (mostly f/w, toothed or bony tongues)	PACHYCORMIFORMES (ray-finned fish with serrated pectoral fins)	PALAEONISCIFORMES (earliest known and most primitive ray-finned forms)	PELTOPLEURIFORMES	PERCIFORMES (bony ray-finned fish with dorsal and anal fins divided into anterior spiny and posterior soft-rayed portions)	PERLEIDIFORMES (bony, diamond-shaped, not-overlaping scales)	PHOLIDOPLEURIFORMES (crushing dentition, long and slender, anal fins far back on the body)	PLEURONECTIFORMES (flatfish, often with both eyes in one side of the head)	POLYMIXIIFORMES (deep-sea marine ray-finned fish with a pair of long hyoid barbels)	PTYCHOLEPIFORMES (spindle-like shape that is wide in the middle and tapes at both ends)	PYCNODONTIFORMES (ray-finned bony fish)	SALMONIFORMES (ray-finned fish including salmon, trout, with pelvic fins far back and having a forked tail)	SAURICHTHYIFORMES (vertical jaw-support)	SCORPAENIFORMES (carnivorous ray-finned fish, called "mail-cheeked")	SEMIONOTIFORMES (primitive freshwater ray-finned fish)	SILURIFORMES (bony catfish)	STOMIIFORMES (deep-sea ray-finned fish)	TARRASIIFORMES	TETRADONTIFORMES (puffers, boxfish; two pairs of large teeth at the front of the jaw)	ZEIFORMES (boarfishes, dories, and john dories)	ACANTHOMORPHA INCERTAE SEDIS (thorn-shaped fish)
